<h1 class=3D"mt-5">The Euclidean Algorithm</h1>
<p class=3D"lead">The basic version of the algorithm. Useful to understand =
the table notation.</p>
<h4>Text or video?</h4>
<p>You can choose to read this page or watch <a href=3D"https://extendedeuc=
lideanalgorithm.com/euclidean.php#video">the video at the bottom of this pa=
ge</a>. Both cover the same material, so there's no need to look at both.
Reading this page might be quicker, but the video could feel a little more =
detailed.</p>

<b>Table of contents:</b><br>
<p>
</p><ul>
<li><a href=3D"https://extendedeuclideanalgorithm.com/euclidean.php#gcdexpl=
">Greatest Common Divisor (gcd)</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://extendedeuclideanalgorithm.com/euclidean.php#euclalg=
">Euclidean Algorithm</a></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://extendedeuclideanalgorithm.com/euclidean.php#eucltab=
le">Euclidean Algorithm in a table</a></li>
</ul>

<hr>
<h4 id=3D"gcdexpl">Greatest Common Divisor (gcd)</h4>
<p>This is the greatest number that divides two other numbers a and b.</p><=
p>

<u>Examples</u>
</p><p>When you have two numbers a and b, with a =3D 8 and b =3D 12, then g=
cd(a, b) =3D gcd(8,12) =3D 4.<br>
Note that gcd(b, a) =3D gcd(a, b), so gcd(12, 8) also equals 4.<br>
Other examples:<br>
gcd(12, 60) =3D 12<br>
gcd(5, 7) =3D 1<br>
gcd(10, 2) =3D 2<br>
gcd(35, 45) =3D 5<br>
gcd(-44, -22) =3D 22.</p>

<p>Note: it's not -22 in the last case, because we are looking for the <b><=
u>greatest</u></b> common divisor. -22 divides them both, but so does 22. A=
nd 22 is greater than -22.</p>

