<u></u><p><u>Properties of the gcd you should remember</u><br>
</p><ol>
<li>gcd(a, b) =3D gcd(b, a)</li>
<li>gcd(a, b) =3D gcd(-a, b) =3D gcd(a, -b) =3D gcd(-a, -b).</li>
<li><mark>gcd(a, b) =3D gcd(b, remainder of (a/b))</mark></li>
<li><mark>gcd(a, 0) =3D |a|</mark> (i.e. the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Absolute_value">absolute value</a> of a)</li>
</ol><p></p>

<p>Property 3 and 4 are important for the Euclidean Algorithm.</p>

<hr>

<h4 id=3D"euclalg">Euclidean Algorithm</h4>
<p>Calculating the gcd of two numbers by hand is more difficult, especially=
 if you have somewhat large numbers.
But using property 3 and 4 mentioned above, we can simplify the calculation=
 of the gcd of two numbers by reducing it to the calculation of the gcd of =
two smaller numbers.</p>

<u>Example</u><br>
<p>Calculate gcd(36, 10).</p>
<p>Using property 3 from above, we know that gcd(36, 10) =3D gcd(10, <u>rem=
ainder of (36/10)</u>).<br>
How do we calculate the remainder of X divided by Y? For now, just use <b>X=
 mod Y</b>.
So in this case the <b>remainder of (36/10)</b> =3D <b>36 mod 10</b> =E2=89=
=A1 6. <br>
So we have gcd(36, 10) =3D gcd(10, remainder of (36/10)) =3D gcd(10, 6).<br=
>
So we get gcd(10, 6), which means we can now simplify gcd(10, 6) the same w=
ay:<br>
gcd(10, 6) =3D gcd(6, remainder of (10/6)) =3D gcd(6, 4).
Similarly, we can now simplify gcd(6, 4) and you'll get gcd(4, 2).
And if you simplify gcd(4, 2), you'll get gcd(2, 0).</p>
<p>Now pay attention to the zero in gcd(2, 0). We want a zero to appear the=
re, because then we can use property 4.<br>
Property 4 states that gcd(a, 0) =3D |a|, so in this case: gcd(2, 0) =3D 2.=
<br>
Now we are done!<br>
We started with gcd(36, 10) and we finished with 2.
So we have just discovered that gcd(36, 10) =3D 2 by using the Euclidean Al=
gorithm.</p>

<p>Here is the same calculation again, but without all that text:<br>
gcd(36, 10) =3D <br>
gcd(10, 6) =3D <br>
gcd(6, 4) =3D <br>
gcd(4, 2) =3D <br>
gcd(2, 0) =3D 2<br>
So gcd(36, 10) =3D 2.</p>

