<h4 id=3D"eucltable">Euclidean algorithm in a table</h4>
<p>In the example above we had to write "gcd" and the parentheses over and =
over again.<br>
This isn't really necessary for the calculation, so we might as well skip i=
t and just write down the numbers in a table.<br>
If we calculate gcd(36, 10) just like we did before, but now we use a table=
 to write down the numbers, it looks like this:</p>

<div class=3D"table-responsive">
  <table class=3D"table table-striped table-bordered">
<thead><tr><th scope=3D"col">a</th><th scope=3D"col">b</th><th scope=3D"col=
">q</th><th scope=3D"col">r</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>36</td><td>10</=
td><td>3</td><td>6</td></tr><tr><td>10</td><td>6</td><td>1</td><td>4</td></=
tr><tr><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>1</td><td>2</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td class=
=3D"table-warning">2</td><td>2</td><td class=3D"table-success">0</td>  </tr=
></tbody>
  </table>
</div>
<!-- <div class=3D"d-lg-none">
You can scroll/swipe horizontally through the table.
</div>-->
<u>What do we see here?</u>
<p>We see 4 columns:
</p><ul>
  <li>Column a and column b:<br>
      The numbers in these first two columns are exactly the same as the nu=
mbers in gcd(..., ...) on each line in our previous calculation.</li>
  <li>Column r (the last column):<br>
      This is the remainder we talked about earlier. We didn't write it dow=
n before, but we did use it for our calculations. So it's handy to write it=
 down.
      So in each row here <b>r</b> is the remainder of (a divided by b) whe=
re a and b are the values in the first two columns on that row. <br>So r =
=E2=89=A1 a mod b.</li>
  <li>The column with the "q"<br>
      This <b>q</b> stands for quotient.<br>
      Just like you can calculate the remainder of X/Y, you can also calcul=
ate the quotient of X/Y.<br> It's not really necessary for the Euclidean al=
gorithm, but we do need it for the Extended Euclidean Algorithm later. So i=
t's better to already get used to it, plus it can be useful when doing the =
Euclidean Algorithm by hand.
</li></ul><p></p>
Also notice that:
<ul>
<li>On each row, a =3D [b from the previous row] and b =3D [r from the prev=
ious row]</li>
<li>In the last row, r=3D0. When <b>r=3D0</b>, you are done and then <b>b</=
b> in that last row is the answer.<br>
So in this case the answer is 2 (like we saw before).<br>
(You could add another row, then the answer is <b>a</b> on that row (since =
then gcd(a, b) =3D gcd(a, 0) =3D |a|). <br>
But that's not necessary, since b already contains that same answer on the =
row where r=3D0).</li>
</ul>


<div class=3D"accordion " id=3D"calcqr">
  <div class=3D"accordion-item">
    <h2 class=3D"accordion-header" id=3D"headingOne">
      <button class=3D"accordion-button collapsed" type=3D"button" data-bs-=
toggle=3D"collapse" data-bs-target=3D"#quotientremainder" aria-expanded=3D"=
false" aria-controls=3D"collapseOne">
        How do we calculate q and r?      </button>
    </h2>
    <div id=3D"quotientremainder" class=3D"accordion-collapse collapse" ari=
a-labelledby=3D"headingOne" data-bs-parent=3D"#accordionExample">
      <div class=3D"accordion-body">
        <p>q =3D quotient of a/b<br>
r =3D remainder of a/b</p>

<p>We said before that remainder of a/b =3D a mod b. <br>
But you can also derive the remainder from the quotient. This can be useful=
 when you do the calculations by hand, or when we need to calculate the quo=
tient anyway (e.g. in the Extended Euclidean Algorithm).<br>
In order to do that, we first need to find the <b>greatest number below a</=
b>, that <b>can be divided by b</b>.<br>
So in the case of a=3D36 and b=3D10, what is the greatest number below 36 t=
hat can be divided by 10?
It's 30. If you divide 30 by 10, you get 3. That's the quotient.</p>

<u>Quotient</u>
<p>So the quotient q =3D [the greatest number below a divisible by b] divid=
ed by b.</p>

<u>Remainder</u>
<p>The remainder r =3D a - [that greatest number below a divisible by b] =
=3D a - (q*b).<br>
So as you can see, once you have q, you can easily calculate r by doing a -=
 (q*b). In this case: 36-(3*10)=3D6</p>

<u>You might wonder:</u>
<p>
</p><ul>
<li>is calculating this quotient really necessary?<br>
Not for the Euclidean algorithm, but it can be useful if you this by hand.<=
br>Also, we do need it for the Extended Euclidean algorithm.</li>
<li>why can't we just use [the greatest number below a divisible by b] in t=
he table instead of q?<br>
For the Euclidean Algorithm, we actually could. But for the Extended Euclid=
ean Algorithm, we need this q for other columns. So it's better to get used=
 to using q, instead of some other number we're not going to use again.</li=
>
</ul>
<p></p>      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>



<br>
<p>At this point you know enough to create your own table. But let's give y=
ou a quick step-by-step overview anyway just to make things clearer.</p>

<div class=3D"accordion " id=3D"accordionExample">
  <div class=3D"accordion-item">
    <h2 class=3D"accordion-header" id=3D"headingOne">
      <button class=3D"accordion-button collapsed" type=3D"button" data-bs-=
toggle=3D"collapse" data-bs-target=3D"#stepbystep" aria-expanded=3D"false" =
aria-controls=3D"collapseOne">
        Step-by-step guide to create a table with the Euclidean algorithm  =
    </button>
    </h2>
    <div id=3D"stepbystep" class=3D"accordion-collapse collapse" aria-label=
ledby=3D"headingOne" data-bs-parent=3D"#accordionExample">
      <div class=3D"accordion-body">
       =20

<p>Let's say you want to calculate gcd(a, b). With a=3D36 and b=3D10 again.=
<br>
Where do we start and when do we stop?</p>
<ul>
<li>Create a table and write down the column names above the columns:<br> a=
, b, q and r.</li>
<li>Then start with the first row. Fill in the numbers for a and b.<br> In =
this case: 36 and 10.</li>
<li>Calculate the quotient.<br>q =3D [the greatest number below a divisible=
 by b] divided by b.<br>In this case: q =3D 30/10=3D3</li>
<li>Calculate the remainder.<br>Use r =3D a-(q*b) or just r=3Da mod b.<br>I=
n this case: r =3D 36-(3*10) =3D 36 mod 10 =3D 6</li>
<li>Now we finished the first row. Let's continue to the next row.<br>Copy =
b and r from the previous row to a and b on this row.<br>
    So a =3D [b from the previous row] =3D 10. And b =3D [r from the previo=
us] row =3D 6.</li>
<li>Now calculate the quotient and the remainder on this row again.</li>
<li>Copy b and r to a and b on the next row again and calculate q and r on =
that row again.</li>
<li>Continue until you have finished a row where r=3D0.<br>If that's the ca=
se, then the answer is <b>b</b> on that row.</li>
</ul><p></p>      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

